        <p>Magnesium is involved in over 300 enzymatic reactions, including those governing muscle contraction and relaxation, protein synthesis, and energy production. Magnesium glycinate is the form with the highest bioavailability and the best-documented effect on sleep quality. The glycine component potentiates GABA (the primary inhibitory neurotransmitter), reducing sleep onset latency and improving deep sleep stage duration. For Athlete-tier athletes with training stress accumulating across multiple sessions per week, magnesium deficiency (common in athletes due to sweat losses) is a silent ceiling on recovery quality.</p>
