<!-- ===================== MODULE 6: THE ATHLETE CHALLENGE ===================== -->
<div class="apn-a-module apn-a-module--dark" id="apn-a-module6">
  <div class="apn-a-wrap">
    <span class="apn-a-section-label" style="color: var(--tier-blue);">The Commitment</span>
    <h2 class="apn-a-h2" style="color:#fff;">Your Athlete Challenge.</h2>
    <div class="apn-a-divider" style="background: var(--tier-blue);"></div>

    <p class="apn-a-body" style="color:rgba(255,255,255,0.7);">
      Four habits. Measurable. Data-verified. Non-negotiable for 30 days. These are the behaviors that define the transition from Athlete to Competitor. They are not harder than what you have already built. They are more precise.
    </p>

    <div style="margin-top:40px;">
      <div class="apn-a-habit">
        <div class="habit-num-a">01</div>
        <div class="habit-content-a">
          <strong>Take a daily HRV reading for 30 consecutive days.</strong>
          <p>Every morning. Before getting out of bed. Log the number. By Day 30 you will have a personal baseline and 30 data points showing how your training load, sleep quality, and recovery protocols are interacting. You will also have had the experience of making at least one training decision based on data rather than feeling. That experience is the point.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="apn-a-habit">
        <div class="habit-num-a">02</div>
        <div class="habit-content-a">
          <strong>Hit 4 distributed protein feedings per day, 5 of 7 days.</strong>
          <p>Each feeding 25g or more. This is not just about total protein. It is about hitting the leucine threshold four times per day, which research shows produces a 35 to 50% greater 24-hour muscle protein synthesis response compared to two large feedings at the same total protein intake. This single change in protein distribution can produce measurable lean mass improvements within a 12-week period.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="apn-a-habit">
        <div class="habit-num-a">03</div>
        <div class="habit-content-a">
          <strong>Log every training session with weights, reps, and a quality score.</strong>
          <p>Quality score is 1 to 5 based on how the session actually went: 1 means significantly below normal output, 3 means normal, 5 means notably above normal. At the end of Week 4, correlate your quality scores with the preceding day's HRV and sleep data. This is how you build your personal performance model. No athlete at the Competitor tier or above trains without data. Start now.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="apn-a-habit">
        <div class="habit-num-a">04</div>
        <div class="habit-content-a">
          <strong>Execute the primary gap protocol without modification for 30 days.</strong>
          <p>The gap MasterClass for your top gap (linked in Module 3 and 7) contains a specific 30-day protocol. Run it exactly as written. Do not modify it based on feeling. Do not add to it. Do not substitute. Changing a protocol before the 30-day mark gives you no data. It just gives you a different untested protocol. Execute. Measure. Then assess.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="apn-a-pullquote" style="margin-top:48px; background: rgba(255,255,255,0.05); border-left-color: var(--tier-blue);">
      <p style="color: rgba(255,255,255,0.85);">"You have built something real. Do not let consistency without precision become your plateau. The athletes who break through this tier are the ones who stop guessing and start measuring."</p>
      <cite>Sutton Huggins, Founder and CEO, Ascend Performance Nutrition</cite>
    </div>

    <div style="margin-top:48px; padding: 32px; background: rgba(6,165,197,0.08); border: 1px solid rgba(6,165,197,0.25); border-radius: 6px;">
      <span class="apn-a-section-label" style="color: var(--tier-blue);">What Separates Athletes Who Level Up</span>
      <p class="apn-a-body" style="color:rgba(255,255,255,0.8); margin-bottom:16px;">
        The Athlete-tier athletes who reach Competitor within 60 days share one consistent characteristic: they are willing to be wrong about where their bottleneck is. They measure, discover their hypothesis was off, adjust the protocol to target the actual constraint, and measure again. The ones who stay at Athlete are convinced they already know what they need to fix and keep doing more of what has already stopped working.
      </p>
      <p class="apn-a-body" style="color:rgba(255,255,255,0.8);">
        Data removes the guessing. Precision removes the plateau. The next tier is not out of reach. It requires a different approach, not more effort.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div style="margin-top:48px; text-align:center;">
      <p style="font-family:var(--font); font-size:15px; color:rgba(255,255,255,0.5); letter-spacing:1px; text-transform:uppercase; margin-bottom:8px;">Conviction Close</p>
      <p style="font-family:var(--font); font-size:18px; color:#fff; line-height:1.7; max-width:560px; margin:0 auto;">Discipline is not just about showing up. At this tier, it is about showing up with data in hand, knowing exactly what you are trying to prove or disprove, and executing with precision. That is what faith-driven performance looks like when the foundation is already built.</p>
    </div>

  </div>
</div>

